window.__XF_SKILL_PACKS__=window.__XF_SKILL_PACKS__||{};window.__XF_SKILL_PACKS__["board-decks-financial-models-pack"]={"id": "board-decks-financial-models-pack", "skills": [{"id": "KPI-dashboard-summary", "aiInstallPrompt": "Install the skill 'KPI-dashboard-summary' by writing the file below.\n\nUniversal path: ./skills/KPI-dashboard-summary/SKILL.md\nGrok path: ~/.grok/skills/KPI-dashboard-summary/SKILL.md\nCursor path: ~/.cursor/skills/KPI-dashboard-summary/SKILL.md\nClaude path: ~/.claude/skills/KPI-dashboard-summary/SKILL.md\nVS Code agent path: .github/skills/KPI-dashboard-summary/SKILL.md\n\nCreate the folder if needed, then write SKILL.md with this exact content:\n\n```markdown\n---\nname: KPI-dashboard-summary\ndescription: >\n  Pulls live KPI data from your connected finance/analytics tool and writes an executive summary that explains the interaction between metrics, not just their individual trend lines. Triggers: \"summarize our KPI dashboard for the exec team\", \"pull the latest KPIs and write me a summary\", /KPI-dashboard-summary.\nmetadata:\n  category: board-decks-financial-models\n  type: connector\n  cadence: monthly\n  risk: low\n  connectors: finance/BI platform (e.g. QuickBooks, Stripe, a BI tool like Looker or a spreadsheet-connected source)\n  integrations: \"@finance-data mentions where KPIs are pulled live\"\nallowed-tools: search_tool, use_tool\n---\n# /KPI-dashboard-summary\n\nPulls live KPI data from your connected finance or BI tool and writes an executive summary that explains how the metrics interact with each other this period - not a list of individual trend lines read in isolation.\n\n## Works with\n\nUse this as a portable `SKILL.md` in Grok, Claude, Cursor, Codex, VS Code agent skills, or any AI workspace that supports reusable markdown instructions. If a tool does not support slash commands, paste the task and ask the AI to follow this skill.\n\n## When to use\n\nAhead of a leadership meeting, monthly close, or board prep, when you need someone (or something) to actually interpret the KPI dashboard rather than just restate what each chart shows - especially useful when two metrics are moving in ways that only make sense together (revenue up but margin down, growth up but retention softening).\n\n## Inputs to gather\n\nCheck context first; ask at most one question if a missing detail changes the interpretation (e.g. \"is the CAC increase this period tied to a specific new channel you're testing?\").\n- Which KPIs matter most for this summary (revenue, growth rate, margin, CAC/LTV, burn/runway, retention - whichever apply to this business)\n- The comparison period (month-over-month, vs. plan, vs. same period last year)\n- Any known business context for the period (a pricing change, a new channel launch, a large one-time expense or revenue item)\n- The audience (exec team, board, investors) since the framing and level of financial detail differ\n\n## Connector access (required)\n\nThis skill cannot run from text alone - it must call live integrations.\n1. Check your AI tool's connector/integration settings (for example: Grok's `/mcps` command, Cursor's MCP settings, Claude's Integrations panel, or your tool's equivalent) and confirm your finance/BI platform is enabled and authenticated. The exact steps vary by tool - if you're not sure how, just ask your AI assistant directly.\n2. Use `search_tool` to discover the available tools for your finance/BI connector in your current session.\n3. Call tools with `use_tool` using the exact tool name your session exposes.\n4. Never claim to have pulled live KPI data without a successful tool call - if the connector isn't available, stop and tell the user which integration to enable, and offer to work from pasted numbers instead.\n\n### Required integrations\n- **@finance-data** - Finance/BI platform (QuickBooks, Stripe, Looker, or equivalent)\n  - Example tools you might see: get_revenue_report, get_kpi_snapshot, query_metric, get_financial_statement\n\n## Workflow\n\n1. Pull all relevant KPIs for the current and comparison periods in one pass, so the summary is built on a consistent data set rather than mixing live-pulled and remembered figures.\n2. Look for metric pairs that only make sense read together - revenue growth alongside gross margin (growing revenue with shrinking margin tells a different story than growing both), new customer acquisition alongside retention/churn (new logo growth masking a retention problem), CAC alongside LTV (CAC creeping up is fine if LTV is rising faster, concerning if it isn't) - and lead the summary with whichever interaction is most material this period.\n3. Explicitly flag any metric that improved in isolation but reflects a trade-off elsewhere (e.g., cutting marketing spend improved burn rate but also slowed pipeline generation) so a reader doesn't take a single green metric at face value without the offsetting cost.\n4. Distinguish a real trend from a one-time or seasonal effect (a large one-off contract, a seasonal dip) so the reader doesn't overreact to noise or underreact to a genuine shift.\n5. State what's driving the period's most important number in plain business terms (not just \"MRR grew 8%\" but \"MRR grew 8%, driven almost entirely by expansion revenue from three existing accounts rather than new logo growth\") since the composition of a metric's movement often matters more than its headline size.\n6. Close with the one or two things worth a deeper look or a decision, flagged explicitly, rather than leaving the reader to infer priority from a flat list of metrics.\n\n## Output format\n\n**KPI Summary - [Period] - [Audience]**\n- Headline (1-2 sentences: the most important interaction or story this period)\n- Key Metrics table: `Metric | This Period | vs. Comparison | Composition/Driver Note`\n- Metric Interactions Worth Noting (pairs that only make sense read together, explained)\n- One-Time/Seasonal Effects to Discount (if any)\n- Worth a Closer Look / Decision Needed (1-2 items, flagged explicitly)\n\n## Do\n- Pull all KPIs through the connector for a consistent, verifiable data set rather than blending live and recalled figures.\n- Actively look for metric pairs that tell a joint story, and lead with the most material interaction.\n- Name the actual composition/driver behind a headline number, not just its size and direction.\n\n## Don't\n- Don't present metrics as an isolated list without checking for interactions between them - that's the main value this skill adds over a raw dashboard.\n- Don't let a single improved metric go unquestioned if it likely reflects a trade-off elsewhere.\n- Don't claim KPI data was pulled live if the connector call failed - fall back to pasted numbers and say so explicitly.\n\n## Quality check (before responding)\n- [ ] Output is copy-paste-ready\n- [ ] Works outside Grok - no unexplained tool-specific assumption left in the text\n- [ ] Connector access verified before claiming results (if applicable)\n- [ ] Approval gate present for any risky/irreversible action (if applicable)\n- [ ] At least one genuine metric interaction (not just individual trend lines) is identified and explained in the summary\n```\n\nAfter writing the file, confirm it exists. The user can then run /KPI-dashboard-summary or describe the task from the skill description.", "skillContent": "---\nname: KPI-dashboard-summary\ndescription: >\n  Pulls live KPI data from your connected finance/analytics tool and writes an executive summary that explains the interaction between metrics, not just their individual trend lines. Triggers: \"summarize our KPI dashboard for the exec team\", \"pull the latest KPIs and write me a summary\", /KPI-dashboard-summary.\nmetadata:\n  category: board-decks-financial-models\n  type: connector\n  cadence: monthly\n  risk: low\n  connectors: finance/BI platform (e.g. QuickBooks, Stripe, a BI tool like Looker or a spreadsheet-connected source)\n  integrations: \"@finance-data mentions where KPIs are pulled live\"\nallowed-tools: search_tool, use_tool\n---\n# /KPI-dashboard-summary\n\nPulls live KPI data from your connected finance or BI tool and writes an executive summary that explains how the metrics interact with each other this period - not a list of individual trend lines read in isolation.\n\n## Works with\n\nUse this as a portable `SKILL.md` in Grok, Claude, Cursor, Codex, VS Code agent skills, or any AI workspace that supports reusable markdown instructions. If a tool does not support slash commands, paste the task and ask the AI to follow this skill.\n\n## When to use\n\nAhead of a leadership meeting, monthly close, or board prep, when you need someone (or something) to actually interpret the KPI dashboard rather than just restate what each chart shows - especially useful when two metrics are moving in ways that only make sense together (revenue up but margin down, growth up but retention softening).\n\n## Inputs to gather\n\nCheck context first; ask at most one question if a missing detail changes the interpretation (e.g. \"is the CAC increase this period tied to a specific new channel you're testing?\").\n- Which KPIs matter most for this summary (revenue, growth rate, margin, CAC/LTV, burn/runway, retention - whichever apply to this business)\n- The comparison period (month-over-month, vs. plan, vs. same period last year)\n- Any known business context for the period (a pricing change, a new channel launch, a large one-time expense or revenue item)\n- The audience (exec team, board, investors) since the framing and level of financial detail differ\n\n## Connector access (required)\n\nThis skill cannot run from text alone - it must call live integrations.\n1. Check your AI tool's connector/integration settings (for example: Grok's `/mcps` command, Cursor's MCP settings, Claude's Integrations panel, or your tool's equivalent) and confirm your finance/BI platform is enabled and authenticated. The exact steps vary by tool - if you're not sure how, just ask your AI assistant directly.\n2. Use `search_tool` to discover the available tools for your finance/BI connector in your current session.\n3. Call tools with `use_tool` using the exact tool name your session exposes.\n4. Never claim to have pulled live KPI data without a successful tool call - if the connector isn't available, stop and tell the user which integration to enable, and offer to work from pasted numbers instead.\n\n### Required integrations\n- **@finance-data** - Finance/BI platform (QuickBooks, Stripe, Looker, or equivalent)\n  - Example tools you might see: get_revenue_report, get_kpi_snapshot, query_metric, get_financial_statement\n\n## Workflow\n\n1. Pull all relevant KPIs for the current and comparison periods in one pass, so the summary is built on a consistent data set rather than mixing live-pulled and remembered figures.\n2. Look for metric pairs that only make sense read together - revenue growth alongside gross margin (growing revenue with shrinking margin tells a different story than growing both), new customer acquisition alongside retention/churn (new logo growth masking a retention problem), CAC alongside LTV (CAC creeping up is fine if LTV is rising faster, concerning if it isn't) - and lead the summary with whichever interaction is most material this period.\n3. Explicitly flag any metric that improved in isolation but reflects a trade-off elsewhere (e.g., cutting marketing spend improved burn rate but also slowed pipeline generation) so a reader doesn't take a single green metric at face value without the offsetting cost.\n4. Distinguish a real trend from a one-time or seasonal effect (a large one-off contract, a seasonal dip) so the reader doesn't overreact to noise or underreact to a genuine shift.\n5. State what's driving the period's most important number in plain business terms (not just \"MRR grew 8%\" but \"MRR grew 8%, driven almost entirely by expansion revenue from three existing accounts rather than new logo growth\") since the composition of a metric's movement often matters more than its headline size.\n6. Close with the one or two things worth a deeper look or a decision, flagged explicitly, rather than leaving the reader to infer priority from a flat list of metrics.\n\n## Output format\n\n**KPI Summary - [Period] - [Audience]**\n- Headline (1-2 sentences: the most important interaction or story this period)\n- Key Metrics table: `Metric | This Period | vs. Comparison | Composition/Driver Note`\n- Metric Interactions Worth Noting (pairs that only make sense read together, explained)\n- One-Time/Seasonal Effects to Discount (if any)\n- Worth a Closer Look / Decision Needed (1-2 items, flagged explicitly)\n\n## Do\n- Pull all KPIs through the connector for a consistent, verifiable data set rather than blending live and recalled figures.\n- Actively look for metric pairs that tell a joint story, and lead with the most material interaction.\n- Name the actual composition/driver behind a headline number, not just its size and direction.\n\n## Don't\n- Don't present metrics as an isolated list without checking for interactions between them - that's the main value this skill adds over a raw dashboard.\n- Don't let a single improved metric go unquestioned if it likely reflects a trade-off elsewhere.\n- Don't claim KPI data was pulled live if the connector call failed - fall back to pasted numbers and say so explicitly.\n\n## Quality check (before responding)\n- [ ] Output is copy-paste-ready\n- [ ] Works outside Grok - no unexplained tool-specific assumption left in the text\n- [ ] Connector access verified before claiming results (if applicable)\n- [ ] Approval gate present for any risky/irreversible action (if applicable)\n- [ ] At least one genuine metric interaction (not just individual trend lines) is identified and explained in the summary\n"}, {"id": "board-update-one-pager", "aiInstallPrompt": "Install the skill 'board-update-one-pager' by writing the file below.\n\nUniversal path: ./skills/board-update-one-pager/SKILL.md\nGrok path: ~/.grok/skills/board-update-one-pager/SKILL.md\nCursor path: ~/.cursor/skills/board-update-one-pager/SKILL.md\nClaude path: ~/.claude/skills/board-update-one-pager/SKILL.md\nVS Code agent path: .github/skills/board-update-one-pager/SKILL.md\n\nCreate the folder if needed, then write SKILL.md with this exact content:\n\n```markdown\n---\nname: board-update-one-pager\ndescription: >\n  Writes a one-page board update that leads with the decisions/asks and treats metrics as supporting evidence, instead of a metrics-first recap board members have to hunt through for what you actually need from them. Triggers: \"write this month's board update\", \"draft a one-pager for the board meeting\", /board-update-one-pager.\nmetadata:\n  category: board-decks-financial-models\n  type: base\n  cadence: monthly\n  risk: medium\n  connectors: \n  integrations: \nallowed-tools: search_tool, use_tool\n---\n# /board-update-one-pager\n\nWrites a one-page board update structured around what you need from the board (decisions, input, awareness) with metrics deployed as supporting evidence for those asks, rather than a metrics recap that leaves the actual ask buried or implicit.\n\n## Works with\n\nUse this as a portable `SKILL.md` in Grok, Claude, Cursor, Codex, VS Code agent skills, or any AI workspace that supports reusable markdown instructions. If a tool does not support slash commands, paste the task and ask the AI to follow this skill.\n\n## When to use\n\nA board meeting is coming up (or a board member wants an async update) and you need a tight one-pager that respects their limited read time and gets specific value out of the interaction - not a status report that could be skipped without anyone missing anything actionable.\n\n## Inputs to gather\n\nCheck context first; ask at most one question if a missing detail changes the structure (e.g. \"is there a specific decision or approval you need from the board this cycle, or is this a pure informational update?\").\n- The period's key metrics and how they compare to the last update and to plan/target\n- Anything you specifically need from the board this cycle - a decision, an intro, a hire approval, a strategic gut-check\n- The single biggest risk or challenge currently facing the business, stated honestly\n- Anything that changed materially since the last update (a pivot, a departure, a new competitor, a major customer win or loss)\n- Board composition/dynamics if relevant (a board member with specific expertise you want to draw on for a specific question)\n\n## Workflow\n\n1. Open with the ask or decision needed from the board this cycle, if there is one, before any metrics - burying the ask in paragraph four is how it gets missed or under-discussed in a time-boxed meeting.\n2. State the single most important headline for the period in one sentence, calibrated honestly to whether it's a genuinely good, bad, or mixed period - board updates that spin every period as uniformly positive lose credibility fast and make board members work harder to find the real signal.\n3. Present metrics as evidence for the headline and the ask, not as an exhaustive data dump - include only the numbers that support the narrative being told this cycle, with a reference appendix for the rest if needed.\n4. Name the single biggest risk directly and specifically (a customer concentration risk, a runway constraint, a key-person dependency) rather than a vague \"we're monitoring market conditions\" - specificity here is what makes a board useful to you, since vague risk framing gets vague help.\n5. If asking for something specific, state exactly what's needed and by when (an intro to a specific type of contact, approval for a specific spend, input on a specific decision) - a vague \"let us know if you have thoughts\" ask rarely produces useful board engagement.\n6. Close with what's coming next cycle in one or two lines, so the board has a preview of what to expect and can flag early if something seems off-track.\n\n## Output format\n\n**Board Update - [Company] - [Month/Period]**\n- The Ask (if any - decision, intro, input needed, with deadline)\n- Headline (1 sentence, honest calibration of the period)\n- Key Metrics (3-5 max, each with vs.-last-period and vs.-plan context)\n- Biggest Risk Right Now (specific, named)\n- What Changed This Period (material changes only)\n- Coming Next Cycle (1-2 lines)\n- Appendix Note (where to find full metrics/detail if the board wants to go deeper)\n\n## Do\n- Lead with the ask, if one exists, before any metrics or narrative.\n- Calibrate the headline honestly to the real period - mixed or bad periods should read as such.\n- Name the biggest risk specifically enough that a board member could actually offer help on it.\n\n## Don't\n- Don't bury a real ask inside a metrics recap where it can be missed in a skim.\n- Don't include every tracked metric; curate to what supports this cycle's specific narrative and ask.\n- Don't soften a genuinely concerning risk into vague language - specific risks get specific help, vague ones get vague nodding.\n\n## Quality check (before responding)\n- [ ] Output is copy-paste-ready\n- [ ] Works outside Grok - no unexplained tool-specific assumption left in the text\n- [ ] Connector access verified before claiming results (if applicable)\n- [ ] Approval gate present for any risky/irreversible action (if applicable)\n- [ ] If there's a real ask this cycle, it appears in the first section, not implied somewhere in the metrics or narrative\n```\n\nAfter writing the file, confirm it exists. The user can then run /board-update-one-pager or describe the task from the skill description.", "skillContent": "---\nname: board-update-one-pager\ndescription: >\n  Writes a one-page board update that leads with the decisions/asks and treats metrics as supporting evidence, instead of a metrics-first recap board members have to hunt through for what you actually need from them. Triggers: \"write this month's board update\", \"draft a one-pager for the board meeting\", /board-update-one-pager.\nmetadata:\n  category: board-decks-financial-models\n  type: base\n  cadence: monthly\n  risk: medium\n  connectors: \n  integrations: \nallowed-tools: search_tool, use_tool\n---\n# /board-update-one-pager\n\nWrites a one-page board update structured around what you need from the board (decisions, input, awareness) with metrics deployed as supporting evidence for those asks, rather than a metrics recap that leaves the actual ask buried or implicit.\n\n## Works with\n\nUse this as a portable `SKILL.md` in Grok, Claude, Cursor, Codex, VS Code agent skills, or any AI workspace that supports reusable markdown instructions. If a tool does not support slash commands, paste the task and ask the AI to follow this skill.\n\n## When to use\n\nA board meeting is coming up (or a board member wants an async update) and you need a tight one-pager that respects their limited read time and gets specific value out of the interaction - not a status report that could be skipped without anyone missing anything actionable.\n\n## Inputs to gather\n\nCheck context first; ask at most one question if a missing detail changes the structure (e.g. \"is there a specific decision or approval you need from the board this cycle, or is this a pure informational update?\").\n- The period's key metrics and how they compare to the last update and to plan/target\n- Anything you specifically need from the board this cycle - a decision, an intro, a hire approval, a strategic gut-check\n- The single biggest risk or challenge currently facing the business, stated honestly\n- Anything that changed materially since the last update (a pivot, a departure, a new competitor, a major customer win or loss)\n- Board composition/dynamics if relevant (a board member with specific expertise you want to draw on for a specific question)\n\n## Workflow\n\n1. Open with the ask or decision needed from the board this cycle, if there is one, before any metrics - burying the ask in paragraph four is how it gets missed or under-discussed in a time-boxed meeting.\n2. State the single most important headline for the period in one sentence, calibrated honestly to whether it's a genuinely good, bad, or mixed period - board updates that spin every period as uniformly positive lose credibility fast and make board members work harder to find the real signal.\n3. Present metrics as evidence for the headline and the ask, not as an exhaustive data dump - include only the numbers that support the narrative being told this cycle, with a reference appendix for the rest if needed.\n4. Name the single biggest risk directly and specifically (a customer concentration risk, a runway constraint, a key-person dependency) rather than a vague \"we're monitoring market conditions\" - specificity here is what makes a board useful to you, since vague risk framing gets vague help.\n5. If asking for something specific, state exactly what's needed and by when (an intro to a specific type of contact, approval for a specific spend, input on a specific decision) - a vague \"let us know if you have thoughts\" ask rarely produces useful board engagement.\n6. Close with what's coming next cycle in one or two lines, so the board has a preview of what to expect and can flag early if something seems off-track.\n\n## Output format\n\n**Board Update - [Company] - [Month/Period]**\n- The Ask (if any - decision, intro, input needed, with deadline)\n- Headline (1 sentence, honest calibration of the period)\n- Key Metrics (3-5 max, each with vs.-last-period and vs.-plan context)\n- Biggest Risk Right Now (specific, named)\n- What Changed This Period (material changes only)\n- Coming Next Cycle (1-2 lines)\n- Appendix Note (where to find full metrics/detail if the board wants to go deeper)\n\n## Do\n- Lead with the ask, if one exists, before any metrics or narrative.\n- Calibrate the headline honestly to the real period - mixed or bad periods should read as such.\n- Name the biggest risk specifically enough that a board member could actually offer help on it.\n\n## Don't\n- Don't bury a real ask inside a metrics recap where it can be missed in a skim.\n- Don't include every tracked metric; curate to what supports this cycle's specific narrative and ask.\n- Don't soften a genuinely concerning risk into vague language - specific risks get specific help, vague ones get vague nodding.\n\n## Quality check (before responding)\n- [ ] Output is copy-paste-ready\n- [ ] Works outside Grok - no unexplained tool-specific assumption left in the text\n- [ ] Connector access verified before claiming results (if applicable)\n- [ ] Approval gate present for any risky/irreversible action (if applicable)\n- [ ] If there's a real ask this cycle, it appears in the first section, not implied somewhere in the metrics or narrative\n"}, {"id": "budget-variance-explainer", "aiInstallPrompt": "Install the skill 'budget-variance-explainer' by writing the file below.\n\nUniversal path: ./skills/budget-variance-explainer/SKILL.md\nGrok path: ~/.grok/skills/budget-variance-explainer/SKILL.md\nCursor path: ~/.cursor/skills/budget-variance-explainer/SKILL.md\nClaude path: ~/.claude/skills/budget-variance-explainer/SKILL.md\nVS Code agent path: .github/skills/budget-variance-explainer/SKILL.md\n\nCreate the folder if needed, then write SKILL.md with this exact content:\n\n```markdown\n---\nname: budget-variance-explainer\ndescription: >\n  Turns a budget-vs-actual variance report into a plain-language explainer that separates timing differences from real overspend and names the specific line items that need a decision. Triggers: \"explain why we're over budget this quarter\", \"write the variance explainer for finance review\", /budget-variance-explainer.\nmetadata:\n  category: board-decks-financial-models\n  type: base\n  cadence: monthly\n  risk: medium\n  connectors: \n  integrations: \nallowed-tools: search_tool, use_tool\n---\n# /budget-variance-explainer\n\nTurns a raw budget-vs-actual variance report into a plain-language explainer that separates real overspend from timing shifts, and flags exactly which line items need a decision versus which are self-correcting noise.\n\n## Works with\n\nUse this as a portable `SKILL.md` in Grok, Claude, Cursor, Codex, VS Code agent skills, or any AI workspace that supports reusable markdown instructions. If a tool does not support slash commands, paste the task and ask the AI to follow this skill.\n\n## When to use\n\nA budget-vs-actual report just came out of finance showing variances across departments/categories, and someone (a department head, the CFO, the exec team) needs a plain-language explanation of what's actually going on before the monthly finance review - especially useful when a raw variance table would otherwise get read line-by-line with no sense of which numbers matter.\n\n## Inputs to gather\n\nCheck context first; ask at most one question if a missing detail changes the read (e.g. \"was this line item's budget phased evenly across the year, or lumpy/seasonal by design?\").\n- The variance report itself (budgeted vs. actual by line item/department, for the period)\n- Whether each budget line was phased evenly across the year or intentionally lumpy (seasonal spend, an annual contract renewal in one month) since this changes what a variance means\n- Any known one-time items in the period (an unplanned expense, a delayed hire, a vendor contract signed early or late)\n- The audience and what decision this explainer is meant to support (a spending freeze decision, a reforecast, just informational review)\n\n## Workflow\n\n1. Separate timing variance from true variance for every line item before characterizing it as over or under budget - a line item that's \"20% over budget this month\" because an annual contract was paid in this month instead of spread across twelve is not actually overspending; it needs to be read against the annual budget pace, not the monthly slice.\n2. For lines with genuine variance (not explained by timing), name the specific driver in plain terms - a new hire that wasn't in the original plan, a vendor price increase, a project that ran over scope - rather than a vague \"spending was higher than expected.\"\n3. Distinguish a one-time variance (a single unusual expense that won't recur) from a run-rate variance (a new ongoing cost level that will persist every future period unless changed) since these require completely different responses - a one-time variance needs acknowledgment, a run-rate variance needs a decision about whether the new spending level is intentional and sustainable.\n4. Flag every run-rate variance explicitly as needing a decision (accept the new baseline, or cut back) rather than letting it pass as just another line in a table, since these are the variances that compound if left unaddressed.\n5. Note any line significantly under budget too, not just over - an under-spend can mean genuine savings, but it can also mean a planned hire didn't happen or a project is delayed, which has its own downstream implications worth flagging.\n6. Roll up to a bottom-line statement: is the organization tracking to its full-period budget overall once timing effects are normalized, even if individual lines look noisy - this is usually the single most important sentence in the whole explainer for a busy reader.\n\n## Output format\n\n**Budget Variance Explainer - [Period] - [Department/Org]**\n- Bottom Line (1-2 sentences: on track / over / under for the full period once timing is normalized)\n- Timing Variances (Not a Real Concern) - table: `Line Item | Monthly Variance | Why It's Timing, Not Real`\n- Real Variances Needing a Look - table: `Line Item | Variance | Driver | One-Time or Run-Rate? | Decision Needed`\n- Notable Under-Spends (and what they might imply - savings vs. delayed plan)\n- Recommended Decisions This Cycle (run-rate variances requiring an accept/cut decision)\n\n## Do\n- Separate timing-driven variance from true variance before drawing any conclusion about over/under spending.\n- Distinguish one-time variances from run-rate variances explicitly - they call for entirely different responses.\n- State the full-period bottom line clearly, since that's what a busy reader actually needs to know first.\n\n## Don't\n- Don't characterize a lumpy, intentionally front-loaded budget line as \"over budget\" without checking its annual pacing first.\n- Don't let a run-rate variance pass as a routine line item - it needs an explicit accept-or-cut decision flagged.\n- Don't ignore significant under-spends; they can signal a delayed plan just as much as a savings win.\n\n## Quality check (before responding)\n- [ ] Output is copy-paste-ready\n- [ ] Works outside Grok - no unexplained tool-specific assumption left in the text\n- [ ] Connector access verified before claiming results (if applicable)\n- [ ] Approval gate present for any risky/irreversible action (if applicable)\n- [ ] Every flagged variance is labeled either timing-driven or real, and every real variance is further labeled one-time or run-rate\n```\n\nAfter writing the file, confirm it exists. The user can then run /budget-variance-explainer or describe the task from the skill description.", "skillContent": "---\nname: budget-variance-explainer\ndescription: >\n  Turns a budget-vs-actual variance report into a plain-language explainer that separates timing differences from real overspend and names the specific line items that need a decision. Triggers: \"explain why we're over budget this quarter\", \"write the variance explainer for finance review\", /budget-variance-explainer.\nmetadata:\n  category: board-decks-financial-models\n  type: base\n  cadence: monthly\n  risk: medium\n  connectors: \n  integrations: \nallowed-tools: search_tool, use_tool\n---\n# /budget-variance-explainer\n\nTurns a raw budget-vs-actual variance report into a plain-language explainer that separates real overspend from timing shifts, and flags exactly which line items need a decision versus which are self-correcting noise.\n\n## Works with\n\nUse this as a portable `SKILL.md` in Grok, Claude, Cursor, Codex, VS Code agent skills, or any AI workspace that supports reusable markdown instructions. If a tool does not support slash commands, paste the task and ask the AI to follow this skill.\n\n## When to use\n\nA budget-vs-actual report just came out of finance showing variances across departments/categories, and someone (a department head, the CFO, the exec team) needs a plain-language explanation of what's actually going on before the monthly finance review - especially useful when a raw variance table would otherwise get read line-by-line with no sense of which numbers matter.\n\n## Inputs to gather\n\nCheck context first; ask at most one question if a missing detail changes the read (e.g. \"was this line item's budget phased evenly across the year, or lumpy/seasonal by design?\").\n- The variance report itself (budgeted vs. actual by line item/department, for the period)\n- Whether each budget line was phased evenly across the year or intentionally lumpy (seasonal spend, an annual contract renewal in one month) since this changes what a variance means\n- Any known one-time items in the period (an unplanned expense, a delayed hire, a vendor contract signed early or late)\n- The audience and what decision this explainer is meant to support (a spending freeze decision, a reforecast, just informational review)\n\n## Workflow\n\n1. Separate timing variance from true variance for every line item before characterizing it as over or under budget - a line item that's \"20% over budget this month\" because an annual contract was paid in this month instead of spread across twelve is not actually overspending; it needs to be read against the annual budget pace, not the monthly slice.\n2. For lines with genuine variance (not explained by timing), name the specific driver in plain terms - a new hire that wasn't in the original plan, a vendor price increase, a project that ran over scope - rather than a vague \"spending was higher than expected.\"\n3. Distinguish a one-time variance (a single unusual expense that won't recur) from a run-rate variance (a new ongoing cost level that will persist every future period unless changed) since these require completely different responses - a one-time variance needs acknowledgment, a run-rate variance needs a decision about whether the new spending level is intentional and sustainable.\n4. Flag every run-rate variance explicitly as needing a decision (accept the new baseline, or cut back) rather than letting it pass as just another line in a table, since these are the variances that compound if left unaddressed.\n5. Note any line significantly under budget too, not just over - an under-spend can mean genuine savings, but it can also mean a planned hire didn't happen or a project is delayed, which has its own downstream implications worth flagging.\n6. Roll up to a bottom-line statement: is the organization tracking to its full-period budget overall once timing effects are normalized, even if individual lines look noisy - this is usually the single most important sentence in the whole explainer for a busy reader.\n\n## Output format\n\n**Budget Variance Explainer - [Period] - [Department/Org]**\n- Bottom Line (1-2 sentences: on track / over / under for the full period once timing is normalized)\n- Timing Variances (Not a Real Concern) - table: `Line Item | Monthly Variance | Why It's Timing, Not Real`\n- Real Variances Needing a Look - table: `Line Item | Variance | Driver | One-Time or Run-Rate? | Decision Needed`\n- Notable Under-Spends (and what they might imply - savings vs. delayed plan)\n- Recommended Decisions This Cycle (run-rate variances requiring an accept/cut decision)\n\n## Do\n- Separate timing-driven variance from true variance before drawing any conclusion about over/under spending.\n- Distinguish one-time variances from run-rate variances explicitly - they call for entirely different responses.\n- State the full-period bottom line clearly, since that's what a busy reader actually needs to know first.\n\n## Don't\n- Don't characterize a lumpy, intentionally front-loaded budget line as \"over budget\" without checking its annual pacing first.\n- Don't let a run-rate variance pass as a routine line item - it needs an explicit accept-or-cut decision flagged.\n- Don't ignore significant under-spends; they can signal a delayed plan just as much as a savings win.\n\n## Quality check (before responding)\n- [ ] Output is copy-paste-ready\n- [ ] Works outside Grok - no unexplained tool-specific assumption left in the text\n- [ ] Connector access verified before claiming results (if applicable)\n- [ ] Approval gate present for any risky/irreversible action (if applicable)\n- [ ] Every flagged variance is labeled either timing-driven or real, and every real variance is further labeled one-time or run-rate\n"}, {"id": "cap-table-summary-memo", "aiInstallPrompt": "Install the skill 'cap-table-summary-memo' by writing the file below.\n\nUniversal path: ./skills/cap-table-summary-memo/SKILL.md\nGrok path: ~/.grok/skills/cap-table-summary-memo/SKILL.md\nCursor path: ~/.cursor/skills/cap-table-summary-memo/SKILL.md\nClaude path: ~/.claude/skills/cap-table-summary-memo/SKILL.md\nVS Code agent path: .github/skills/cap-table-summary-memo/SKILL.md\n\nCreate the folder if needed, then write SKILL.md with this exact content:\n\n```markdown\n---\nname: cap-table-summary-memo\ndescription: >\n  Turns a raw cap table into a plain-language memo explaining ownership, dilution impact of a proposed round, and any structural issues (option pool sizing, liquidation stack) before terms get negotiated. Triggers: \"explain our cap table before this raise\", \"write a memo on how this new round dilutes existing holders\", /cap-table-summary-memo.\nmetadata:\n  category: board-decks-financial-models\n  type: base\n  cadence: on-demand\n  risk: high\n  connectors: \n  integrations: \nallowed-tools: search_tool, use_tool\n---\n# /cap-table-summary-memo\n\nTurns a raw cap table (and, if applicable, a proposed new round's terms) into a plain-language memo explaining current ownership, how a proposed round would dilute each holder class, and any structural issues worth flagging before terms are finalized.\n\n## Works with\n\nUse this as a portable `SKILL.md` in Grok, Claude, Cursor, Codex, VS Code agent skills, or any AI workspace that supports reusable markdown instructions. If a tool does not support slash commands, paste the task and ask the AI to follow this skill.\n\n## When to use\n\nBefore a board discussion on a new financing round, before extending or negotiating a term sheet, or when a founder/exec needs to understand exactly how a proposed raise changes who owns what and whether the option pool or liquidation stack needs attention before signing anything.\n\n## Inputs to gather\n\nCheck context first; ask at most one question if a missing detail changes the memo (e.g. \"is the new round's option pool top-up coming out of pre-money or post-money?\").\n- The current cap table: holder classes (founders, employees/option pool, prior investors by round), share counts, and any existing liquidation preferences\n- The proposed new round's terms if applicable: amount raised, pre/post-money valuation, whether an option pool top-up is included and its sizing\n- Whether this memo is for internal planning, a board discussion, or to walk a specific stakeholder (a founder, a new hire being granted options) through their position\n- Any known structural complexity already in place (multiple liquidation preference stacks, participating preferred, anti-dilution provisions)\n\n## Safety\n\n- Propose before acting: present the memo for review before it's used to inform any negotiation position or shared with counterparties.\n- Never take an irreversible action (agreeing to terms, sending figures externally) without the user explicitly confirming the numbers and framing first - cap table math errors have real financial consequences.\n\n## Workflow\n\n1. State current ownership by holder class as both share count and fully-diluted percentage, since raw share counts without the fully-diluted context are frequently misleading (a founder can hold a large absolute share count and a shrinking percentage simultaneously).\n2. If a new round is proposed, calculate the specific dilution impact on each existing holder class separately - founders, employees, and each prior investor round typically dilute differently depending on pro-rata participation and pool top-up mechanics, and lumping them into one \"average dilution\" figure hides who's actually affected most.\n3. Check the option pool sizing explicitly and flag if a pool top-up is being created \"pre-money\" (meaning existing shareholders, not the new investor, absorb the dilution from the expanded pool) since this mechanic is a common point of founder surprise and deserves its own clear callout, not a buried line item.\n4. Check the liquidation preference stack and flag anything that changes the effective payout order or economics in a downside or modest-upside exit scenario - a memo that only discusses ownership percentage without checking the liquidation stack misses the scenario where percentage ownership and actual payout diverge significantly.\n5. Flag any anti-dilution provisions from prior rounds that could be triggered by this round's price (a down round or flat round relative to a prior round with full-ratchet or broad-based weighted average protection) since this can materially change the dilution math beyond the headline percentages.\n6. Present the \"who gets diluted, by how much, and why\" as the central plain-language narrative of the memo, with the detailed table as supporting backup, since this is the question every stakeholder actually wants answered and a table alone doesn't answer it.\n7. Note explicitly that this memo is a planning aid, not a substitute for legal/tax counsel review of the actual round documents before anything is signed.\n\n## Output format\n\n**Cap Table Summary Memo - [Company] - [Date/Round Context]**\n- Current Ownership table: `Holder Class | Shares | Fully-Diluted % `\n- Proposed Round Terms Summary (if applicable): amount, pre/post-money, pool top-up mechanics\n- Dilution Impact by Holder Class table: `Holder Class | Current % | Post-Round % | Change`\n- Option Pool Top-Up Flag (pre-money vs. post-money mechanic, and who absorbs it)\n- Liquidation Stack Notes (order, any participating preferred, downside scenario implication)\n- Anti-Dilution Trigger Check (any prior-round provisions activated by this round's terms)\n- Note: This memo supports planning discussion; final terms require legal/tax counsel review\n\n## Do\n- Break down dilution by holder class specifically, never as one blended average percentage.\n- Flag pre-money vs. post-money option pool top-up mechanics explicitly - it's a frequent source of founder surprise.\n- Note plainly that this memo doesn't substitute for legal/tax review before signing anything.\n\n## Don't\n- Don't present ownership as raw share counts alone without the fully-diluted percentage context.\n- Don't skip the liquidation preference stack check - ownership percentage and actual payout can diverge sharply in some exit scenarios.\n- Don't treat this memo's output as final legal guidance; it's a planning and communication aid.\n\n## Quality check (before responding)\n- [ ] Output is copy-paste-ready\n- [ ] Works outside Grok - no unexplained tool-specific assumption left in the text\n- [ ] Connector access verified before claiming results (if applicable)\n- [ ] Approval gate present for any risky/irreversible action (if applicable)\n- [ ] Dilution impact is broken out per holder class, and the option pool top-up mechanic is explicitly flagged as pre- or post-money\n```\n\nAfter writing the file, confirm it exists. The user can then run /cap-table-summary-memo or describe the task from the skill description.", "skillContent": "---\nname: cap-table-summary-memo\ndescription: >\n  Turns a raw cap table into a plain-language memo explaining ownership, dilution impact of a proposed round, and any structural issues (option pool sizing, liquidation stack) before terms get negotiated. Triggers: \"explain our cap table before this raise\", \"write a memo on how this new round dilutes existing holders\", /cap-table-summary-memo.\nmetadata:\n  category: board-decks-financial-models\n  type: base\n  cadence: on-demand\n  risk: high\n  connectors: \n  integrations: \nallowed-tools: search_tool, use_tool\n---\n# /cap-table-summary-memo\n\nTurns a raw cap table (and, if applicable, a proposed new round's terms) into a plain-language memo explaining current ownership, how a proposed round would dilute each holder class, and any structural issues worth flagging before terms are finalized.\n\n## Works with\n\nUse this as a portable `SKILL.md` in Grok, Claude, Cursor, Codex, VS Code agent skills, or any AI workspace that supports reusable markdown instructions. If a tool does not support slash commands, paste the task and ask the AI to follow this skill.\n\n## When to use\n\nBefore a board discussion on a new financing round, before extending or negotiating a term sheet, or when a founder/exec needs to understand exactly how a proposed raise changes who owns what and whether the option pool or liquidation stack needs attention before signing anything.\n\n## Inputs to gather\n\nCheck context first; ask at most one question if a missing detail changes the memo (e.g. \"is the new round's option pool top-up coming out of pre-money or post-money?\").\n- The current cap table: holder classes (founders, employees/option pool, prior investors by round), share counts, and any existing liquidation preferences\n- The proposed new round's terms if applicable: amount raised, pre/post-money valuation, whether an option pool top-up is included and its sizing\n- Whether this memo is for internal planning, a board discussion, or to walk a specific stakeholder (a founder, a new hire being granted options) through their position\n- Any known structural complexity already in place (multiple liquidation preference stacks, participating preferred, anti-dilution provisions)\n\n## Safety\n\n- Propose before acting: present the memo for review before it's used to inform any negotiation position or shared with counterparties.\n- Never take an irreversible action (agreeing to terms, sending figures externally) without the user explicitly confirming the numbers and framing first - cap table math errors have real financial consequences.\n\n## Workflow\n\n1. State current ownership by holder class as both share count and fully-diluted percentage, since raw share counts without the fully-diluted context are frequently misleading (a founder can hold a large absolute share count and a shrinking percentage simultaneously).\n2. If a new round is proposed, calculate the specific dilution impact on each existing holder class separately - founders, employees, and each prior investor round typically dilute differently depending on pro-rata participation and pool top-up mechanics, and lumping them into one \"average dilution\" figure hides who's actually affected most.\n3. Check the option pool sizing explicitly and flag if a pool top-up is being created \"pre-money\" (meaning existing shareholders, not the new investor, absorb the dilution from the expanded pool) since this mechanic is a common point of founder surprise and deserves its own clear callout, not a buried line item.\n4. Check the liquidation preference stack and flag anything that changes the effective payout order or economics in a downside or modest-upside exit scenario - a memo that only discusses ownership percentage without checking the liquidation stack misses the scenario where percentage ownership and actual payout diverge significantly.\n5. Flag any anti-dilution provisions from prior rounds that could be triggered by this round's price (a down round or flat round relative to a prior round with full-ratchet or broad-based weighted average protection) since this can materially change the dilution math beyond the headline percentages.\n6. Present the \"who gets diluted, by how much, and why\" as the central plain-language narrative of the memo, with the detailed table as supporting backup, since this is the question every stakeholder actually wants answered and a table alone doesn't answer it.\n7. Note explicitly that this memo is a planning aid, not a substitute for legal/tax counsel review of the actual round documents before anything is signed.\n\n## Output format\n\n**Cap Table Summary Memo - [Company] - [Date/Round Context]**\n- Current Ownership table: `Holder Class | Shares | Fully-Diluted % `\n- Proposed Round Terms Summary (if applicable): amount, pre/post-money, pool top-up mechanics\n- Dilution Impact by Holder Class table: `Holder Class | Current % | Post-Round % | Change`\n- Option Pool Top-Up Flag (pre-money vs. post-money mechanic, and who absorbs it)\n- Liquidation Stack Notes (order, any participating preferred, downside scenario implication)\n- Anti-Dilution Trigger Check (any prior-round provisions activated by this round's terms)\n- Note: This memo supports planning discussion; final terms require legal/tax counsel review\n\n## Do\n- Break down dilution by holder class specifically, never as one blended average percentage.\n- Flag pre-money vs. post-money option pool top-up mechanics explicitly - it's a frequent source of founder surprise.\n- Note plainly that this memo doesn't substitute for legal/tax review before signing anything.\n\n## Don't\n- Don't present ownership as raw share counts alone without the fully-diluted percentage context.\n- Don't skip the liquidation preference stack check - ownership percentage and actual payout can diverge sharply in some exit scenarios.\n- Don't treat this memo's output as final legal guidance; it's a planning and communication aid.\n\n## Quality check (before responding)\n- [ ] Output is copy-paste-ready\n- [ ] Works outside Grok - no unexplained tool-specific assumption left in the text\n- [ ] Connector access verified before claiming results (if applicable)\n- [ ] Approval gate present for any risky/irreversible action (if applicable)\n- [ ] Dilution impact is broken out per holder class, and the option pool top-up mechanic is explicitly flagged as pre- or post-money\n"}, {"id": "fundraising-deck-appendix", "aiInstallPrompt": "Install the skill 'fundraising-deck-appendix' by writing the file below.\n\nUniversal path: ./skills/fundraising-deck-appendix/SKILL.md\nGrok path: ~/.grok/skills/fundraising-deck-appendix/SKILL.md\nCursor path: ~/.cursor/skills/fundraising-deck-appendix/SKILL.md\nClaude path: ~/.claude/skills/fundraising-deck-appendix/SKILL.md\nVS Code agent path: .github/skills/fundraising-deck-appendix/SKILL.md\n\nCreate the folder if needed, then write SKILL.md with this exact content:\n\n```markdown\n---\nname: fundraising-deck-appendix\ndescription: >\n  Builds the fundraising deck appendix section that pre-answers the specific diligence questions investors always ask, so the follow-up call spends less time on data requests and more on the actual pitch. Triggers: \"build the appendix for our pitch deck\", \"what should go in the backup slides for investors\", /fundraising-deck-appendix.\nmetadata:\n  category: board-decks-financial-models\n  type: base\n  cadence: on-demand\n  risk: medium\n  connectors: \n  integrations: \nallowed-tools: search_tool, use_tool\n---\n# /fundraising-deck-appendix\n\nBuilds the backup/appendix section of a fundraising deck, structured around the specific diligence questions investors reliably ask after the core pitch, so those slides are ready before the question is asked rather than promised as a follow-up.\n\n## Works with\n\nUse this as a portable `SKILL.md` in Grok, Claude, Cursor, Codex, VS Code agent skills, or any AI workspace that supports reusable markdown instructions. If a tool does not support slash commands, paste the task and ask the AI to follow this skill.\n\n## When to use\n\nThe core pitch deck narrative is done and you're preparing the backup slides that won't be presented live but need to be ready when an investor asks a specific diligence question in the room or over email - the goal is minimizing \"let me get back to you on that\" moments during a live conversation.\n\n## Inputs to gather\n\nCheck context first; ask at most one question if a missing detail changes the appendix scope (e.g. \"is this for a first pitch meeting or for a partner meeting further into diligence?\").\n- The core deck's narrative and the stage of fundraising (pre-seed, seed, Series A+) since diligence depth expected differs sharply by stage\n- The actual underlying numbers available: unit economics, cohort data, burn/runway, cap table, customer concentration, pipeline detail\n- Any question already asked by an investor in a prior meeting that should clearly get its own backup slide\n- Anything sensitive that needs careful framing rather than omission (customer concentration risk, a past down round, a co-founder departure)\n\n## Workflow\n\n1. Build the appendix around the standard diligence question set for this specific stage - pre-seed/seed appendices lean toward founder-market fit, early user feedback detail, and a credible go-to-market plan; Series A+ appendices need unit economics by cohort, sales efficiency metrics, and churn/retention detail - rather than a generic backup slide set copied across stages.\n2. For every sensitive or potentially concerning data point (customer concentration, a longer-than-average sales cycle, a competitor with more funding), build the slide to address it directly with context and mitigation rather than omitting it and hoping it doesn't come up - investors who find an omitted red flag themselves trust the raise less than one addressed proactively.\n3. Include a cohort-based view of retention/usage wherever the business model supports it, since aggregate metrics alone (blended churn, average retention) are a common diligence red flag investors probe past almost immediately.\n4. Build a specific unit economics slide (CAC, LTV, payback period, gross margin) with the underlying assumptions shown, not just the output numbers, since sophisticated investors will ask what's behind the calculation and an appendix slide that shows its work builds more trust than one that doesn't.\n5. Include a \"use of funds\" slide with actual specificity (roles being hired, by when, tied to milestones the round is meant to achieve) rather than generic percentage buckets (40% engineering, 30% sales) with no milestone connection.\n6. Add a competitive-positioning slide that names real competitors honestly, including their genuine strengths, rather than a dismissive comparison chart where every competitor conveniently loses on every axis - investors read a strawman competitive slide as a credibility flag.\n7. Anticipate the single hardest question this specific company will get (based on its actual weak point - early revenue, a concentrated customer base, an unproven channel) and build a dedicated slide addressing it directly, since deflecting a known hard question live reads worse than addressing it in a prepared slide.\n\n## Output format\n\n**Fundraising Deck Appendix - [Company] - [Round Stage]**\n- Slide List (ordered): Unit Economics (with assumptions shown) / Cohort Retention / Use of Funds (milestone-tied) / Competitive Positioning (honest) / Customer Concentration & Mitigation (if relevant) / Cap Table Summary / [Any Stage-Specific Additions]\n- For Each Slide: Core Data/Claim + the Specific Investor Question It Pre-Answers\n- Hardest Anticipated Question and Its Dedicated Slide (named explicitly)\n\n## Do\n- Address known weak points and sensitive data directly with context, rather than omitting them from the appendix.\n- Show the assumptions behind unit economics numbers, not just the output figures.\n- Use real, honestly-described competitors on the competitive slide, including their genuine strengths.\n\n## Don't\n- Don't build a generic appendix template reused across every stage of fundraising - tailor slide depth to what this stage's investors actually diligence.\n- Don't build a strawman competitive comparison where the company wins on every listed axis - it undermines credibility rather than building it.\n- Don't leave the hardest, most anticipated question unaddressed hoping it won't come up - build a slide for it.\n\n## Quality check (before responding)\n- [ ] Output is copy-paste-ready\n- [ ] Works outside Grok - no unexplained tool-specific assumption left in the text\n- [ ] Connector access verified before claiming results (if applicable)\n- [ ] Approval gate present for any risky/irreversible action (if applicable)\n- [ ] The single hardest anticipated question for this specific company is named and given its own dedicated slide, not left unaddressed\n```\n\nAfter writing the file, confirm it exists. The user can then run /fundraising-deck-appendix or describe the task from the skill description.", "skillContent": "---\nname: fundraising-deck-appendix\ndescription: >\n  Builds the fundraising deck appendix section that pre-answers the specific diligence questions investors always ask, so the follow-up call spends less time on data requests and more on the actual pitch. Triggers: \"build the appendix for our pitch deck\", \"what should go in the backup slides for investors\", /fundraising-deck-appendix.\nmetadata:\n  category: board-decks-financial-models\n  type: base\n  cadence: on-demand\n  risk: medium\n  connectors: \n  integrations: \nallowed-tools: search_tool, use_tool\n---\n# /fundraising-deck-appendix\n\nBuilds the backup/appendix section of a fundraising deck, structured around the specific diligence questions investors reliably ask after the core pitch, so those slides are ready before the question is asked rather than promised as a follow-up.\n\n## Works with\n\nUse this as a portable `SKILL.md` in Grok, Claude, Cursor, Codex, VS Code agent skills, or any AI workspace that supports reusable markdown instructions. If a tool does not support slash commands, paste the task and ask the AI to follow this skill.\n\n## When to use\n\nThe core pitch deck narrative is done and you're preparing the backup slides that won't be presented live but need to be ready when an investor asks a specific diligence question in the room or over email - the goal is minimizing \"let me get back to you on that\" moments during a live conversation.\n\n## Inputs to gather\n\nCheck context first; ask at most one question if a missing detail changes the appendix scope (e.g. \"is this for a first pitch meeting or for a partner meeting further into diligence?\").\n- The core deck's narrative and the stage of fundraising (pre-seed, seed, Series A+) since diligence depth expected differs sharply by stage\n- The actual underlying numbers available: unit economics, cohort data, burn/runway, cap table, customer concentration, pipeline detail\n- Any question already asked by an investor in a prior meeting that should clearly get its own backup slide\n- Anything sensitive that needs careful framing rather than omission (customer concentration risk, a past down round, a co-founder departure)\n\n## Workflow\n\n1. Build the appendix around the standard diligence question set for this specific stage - pre-seed/seed appendices lean toward founder-market fit, early user feedback detail, and a credible go-to-market plan; Series A+ appendices need unit economics by cohort, sales efficiency metrics, and churn/retention detail - rather than a generic backup slide set copied across stages.\n2. For every sensitive or potentially concerning data point (customer concentration, a longer-than-average sales cycle, a competitor with more funding), build the slide to address it directly with context and mitigation rather than omitting it and hoping it doesn't come up - investors who find an omitted red flag themselves trust the raise less than one addressed proactively.\n3. Include a cohort-based view of retention/usage wherever the business model supports it, since aggregate metrics alone (blended churn, average retention) are a common diligence red flag investors probe past almost immediately.\n4. Build a specific unit economics slide (CAC, LTV, payback period, gross margin) with the underlying assumptions shown, not just the output numbers, since sophisticated investors will ask what's behind the calculation and an appendix slide that shows its work builds more trust than one that doesn't.\n5. Include a \"use of funds\" slide with actual specificity (roles being hired, by when, tied to milestones the round is meant to achieve) rather than generic percentage buckets (40% engineering, 30% sales) with no milestone connection.\n6. Add a competitive-positioning slide that names real competitors honestly, including their genuine strengths, rather than a dismissive comparison chart where every competitor conveniently loses on every axis - investors read a strawman competitive slide as a credibility flag.\n7. Anticipate the single hardest question this specific company will get (based on its actual weak point - early revenue, a concentrated customer base, an unproven channel) and build a dedicated slide addressing it directly, since deflecting a known hard question live reads worse than addressing it in a prepared slide.\n\n## Output format\n\n**Fundraising Deck Appendix - [Company] - [Round Stage]**\n- Slide List (ordered): Unit Economics (with assumptions shown) / Cohort Retention / Use of Funds (milestone-tied) / Competitive Positioning (honest) / Customer Concentration & Mitigation (if relevant) / Cap Table Summary / [Any Stage-Specific Additions]\n- For Each Slide: Core Data/Claim + the Specific Investor Question It Pre-Answers\n- Hardest Anticipated Question and Its Dedicated Slide (named explicitly)\n\n## Do\n- Address known weak points and sensitive data directly with context, rather than omitting them from the appendix.\n- Show the assumptions behind unit economics numbers, not just the output figures.\n- Use real, honestly-described competitors on the competitive slide, including their genuine strengths.\n\n## Don't\n- Don't build a generic appendix template reused across every stage of fundraising - tailor slide depth to what this stage's investors actually diligence.\n- Don't build a strawman competitive comparison where the company wins on every listed axis - it undermines credibility rather than building it.\n- Don't leave the hardest, most anticipated question unaddressed hoping it won't come up - build a slide for it.\n\n## Quality check (before responding)\n- [ ] Output is copy-paste-ready\n- [ ] Works outside Grok - no unexplained tool-specific assumption left in the text\n- [ ] Connector access verified before claiming results (if applicable)\n- [ ] Approval gate present for any risky/irreversible action (if applicable)\n- [ ] The single hardest anticipated question for this specific company is named and given its own dedicated slide, not left unaddressed\n"}, {"id": "investor-update-email", "aiInstallPrompt": "Install the skill 'investor-update-email' by writing the file below.\n\nUniversal path: ./skills/investor-update-email/SKILL.md\nGrok path: ~/.grok/skills/investor-update-email/SKILL.md\nCursor path: ~/.cursor/skills/investor-update-email/SKILL.md\nClaude path: ~/.claude/skills/investor-update-email/SKILL.md\nVS Code agent path: .github/skills/investor-update-email/SKILL.md\n\nCreate the folder if needed, then write SKILL.md with this exact content:\n\n```markdown\n---\nname: investor-update-email\ndescription: >\n  Writes a regular investor update email structured to actually get investors to open, read, and act (intros, referrals, advice) on specific asks, instead of a metrics recap that gets skimmed and archived. Triggers: \"write this month's investor update email\", \"draft our quarterly update to investors\", /investor-update-email.\nmetadata:\n  category: board-decks-financial-models\n  type: base\n  cadence: monthly\n  risk: medium\n  connectors: \n  integrations: \nallowed-tools: search_tool, use_tool\n---\n# /investor-update-email\n\nWrites a regular investor update email structured around specific, actionable asks placed where investors will actually see them, with metrics and narrative as supporting context rather than the entire point of the email.\n\n## Works with\n\nUse this as a portable `SKILL.md` in Grok, Claude, Cursor, Codex, VS Code agent skills, or any AI workspace that supports reusable markdown instructions. If a tool does not support slash commands, paste the task and ask the AI to follow this skill.\n\n## When to use\n\nYour regular cadence (monthly or quarterly) investor update is due, and you want it to do real work - generate warm intros, useful advice, or candidate referrals from a busy investor base - rather than reading as a status report that gets skimmed on a phone and archived without action.\n\n## Inputs to gather\n\nCheck context first; ask at most one question if a missing detail changes the email (e.g. \"do you have a specific type of intro or hire you need help with this cycle, or is this a pure informational update?\").\n- This period's key metrics and how they compare to plan and last update\n- Specific asks for this cycle (an intro to a type of company/person, help evaluating a candidate, industry intel on a competitor or market shift, advice on a specific decision)\n- The single most important win and the single most important challenge this period, stated honestly\n- Investor list characteristics if relevant (a mix of lead investors, angels, strategics who might each be useful for different asks)\n\n## Workflow\n\n1. Put the specific ask(s) near the top of the email, immediately after a one-line headline, rather than at the bottom after a full metrics recap - investors skimming on a phone often don't reach the bottom, and an ask buried there effectively never gets read.\n2. Make every ask concrete and easy to act on in under a minute - name the exact type of company/role/person needed for an intro request, rather than a vague \"let us know if you know anyone helpful,\" which requires the investor to do the work of figuring out what would actually help.\n3. State the period's headline honestly, calibrated to whether it was genuinely a good, mixed, or difficult period - investor updates that read as uniformly positive every single cycle lose credibility and train investors to skim past the narrative section entirely.\n4. Name the single biggest current challenge specifically (not \"the market is tough\" but the actual specific obstacle) since a specific, well-articulated challenge is often what prompts an investor to proactively offer help beyond whatever was explicitly asked for.\n5. Keep the metrics section short and comparative (this period vs. last, vs. plan) rather than an exhaustive dashboard dump - investors who want to go deeper can ask, and a long metrics wall discourages reading the parts of the email that actually need a response.\n6. Close with a clear, low-friction way to respond to the ask (a specific reply-to question, a calendar link, a name to connect via email) so acting on the ask takes the investor the least possible effort.\n\n## Output format\n\n**Investor Update - [Company] - [Month/Quarter]**\n- Headline (1 sentence, honestly calibrated)\n- The Ask(s) This Cycle (specific, concrete, each with an easy way to respond)\n- Key Metrics (3-5, this period vs. last vs. plan)\n- Biggest Win This Period\n- Biggest Challenge Right Now (named specifically)\n- Coming Next Cycle (1-2 lines)\n\n## Do\n- Place the specific, actionable ask near the top, right after the headline.\n- Calibrate the headline and challenge sections honestly, even in a rough period.\n- Make every ask something an investor could act on in under a minute.\n\n## Don't\n- Don't bury the ask at the bottom of a long metrics-first email where it's likely to go unread.\n- Don't write a vague catch-all ask (\"let us know if you can help\") that puts the thinking burden back on the investor.\n- Don't present every period as uniformly positive; it erodes the credibility investors need to actually engage with future updates.\n\n## Quality check (before responding)\n- [ ] Output is copy-paste-ready\n- [ ] Works outside Grok - no unexplained tool-specific assumption left in the text\n- [ ] Connector access verified before claiming results (if applicable)\n- [ ] Approval gate present for any risky/irreversible action (if applicable)\n- [ ] Every ask is specific enough that an investor could act on it in under a minute, and appears before the metrics section\n```\n\nAfter writing the file, confirm it exists. The user can then run /investor-update-email or describe the task from the skill description.", "skillContent": "---\nname: investor-update-email\ndescription: >\n  Writes a regular investor update email structured to actually get investors to open, read, and act (intros, referrals, advice) on specific asks, instead of a metrics recap that gets skimmed and archived. Triggers: \"write this month's investor update email\", \"draft our quarterly update to investors\", /investor-update-email.\nmetadata:\n  category: board-decks-financial-models\n  type: base\n  cadence: monthly\n  risk: medium\n  connectors: \n  integrations: \nallowed-tools: search_tool, use_tool\n---\n# /investor-update-email\n\nWrites a regular investor update email structured around specific, actionable asks placed where investors will actually see them, with metrics and narrative as supporting context rather than the entire point of the email.\n\n## Works with\n\nUse this as a portable `SKILL.md` in Grok, Claude, Cursor, Codex, VS Code agent skills, or any AI workspace that supports reusable markdown instructions. If a tool does not support slash commands, paste the task and ask the AI to follow this skill.\n\n## When to use\n\nYour regular cadence (monthly or quarterly) investor update is due, and you want it to do real work - generate warm intros, useful advice, or candidate referrals from a busy investor base - rather than reading as a status report that gets skimmed on a phone and archived without action.\n\n## Inputs to gather\n\nCheck context first; ask at most one question if a missing detail changes the email (e.g. \"do you have a specific type of intro or hire you need help with this cycle, or is this a pure informational update?\").\n- This period's key metrics and how they compare to plan and last update\n- Specific asks for this cycle (an intro to a type of company/person, help evaluating a candidate, industry intel on a competitor or market shift, advice on a specific decision)\n- The single most important win and the single most important challenge this period, stated honestly\n- Investor list characteristics if relevant (a mix of lead investors, angels, strategics who might each be useful for different asks)\n\n## Workflow\n\n1. Put the specific ask(s) near the top of the email, immediately after a one-line headline, rather than at the bottom after a full metrics recap - investors skimming on a phone often don't reach the bottom, and an ask buried there effectively never gets read.\n2. Make every ask concrete and easy to act on in under a minute - name the exact type of company/role/person needed for an intro request, rather than a vague \"let us know if you know anyone helpful,\" which requires the investor to do the work of figuring out what would actually help.\n3. State the period's headline honestly, calibrated to whether it was genuinely a good, mixed, or difficult period - investor updates that read as uniformly positive every single cycle lose credibility and train investors to skim past the narrative section entirely.\n4. Name the single biggest current challenge specifically (not \"the market is tough\" but the actual specific obstacle) since a specific, well-articulated challenge is often what prompts an investor to proactively offer help beyond whatever was explicitly asked for.\n5. Keep the metrics section short and comparative (this period vs. last, vs. plan) rather than an exhaustive dashboard dump - investors who want to go deeper can ask, and a long metrics wall discourages reading the parts of the email that actually need a response.\n6. Close with a clear, low-friction way to respond to the ask (a specific reply-to question, a calendar link, a name to connect via email) so acting on the ask takes the investor the least possible effort.\n\n## Output format\n\n**Investor Update - [Company] - [Month/Quarter]**\n- Headline (1 sentence, honestly calibrated)\n- The Ask(s) This Cycle (specific, concrete, each with an easy way to respond)\n- Key Metrics (3-5, this period vs. last vs. plan)\n- Biggest Win This Period\n- Biggest Challenge Right Now (named specifically)\n- Coming Next Cycle (1-2 lines)\n\n## Do\n- Place the specific, actionable ask near the top, right after the headline.\n- Calibrate the headline and challenge sections honestly, even in a rough period.\n- Make every ask something an investor could act on in under a minute.\n\n## Don't\n- Don't bury the ask at the bottom of a long metrics-first email where it's likely to go unread.\n- Don't write a vague catch-all ask (\"let us know if you can help\") that puts the thinking burden back on the investor.\n- Don't present every period as uniformly positive; it erodes the credibility investors need to actually engage with future updates.\n\n## Quality check (before responding)\n- [ ] Output is copy-paste-ready\n- [ ] Works outside Grok - no unexplained tool-specific assumption left in the text\n- [ ] Connector access verified before claiming results (if applicable)\n- [ ] Approval gate present for any risky/irreversible action (if applicable)\n- [ ] Every ask is specific enough that an investor could act on it in under a minute, and appears before the metrics section\n"}, {"id": "runway-scenario-comparison", "aiInstallPrompt": "Install the skill 'runway-scenario-comparison' by writing the file below.\n\nUniversal path: ./skills/runway-scenario-comparison/SKILL.md\nGrok path: ~/.grok/skills/runway-scenario-comparison/SKILL.md\nCursor path: ~/.cursor/skills/runway-scenario-comparison/SKILL.md\nClaude path: ~/.claude/skills/runway-scenario-comparison/SKILL.md\nVS Code agent path: .github/skills/runway-scenario-comparison/SKILL.md\n\nCreate the folder if needed, then write SKILL.md with this exact content:\n\n```markdown\n---\nname: runway-scenario-comparison\ndescription: >\n  Compares runway under multiple spend/growth scenarios and names the specific operational trade-off behind each extra month of runway, instead of a single runway number with no visibility into what buys more time. Triggers: \"compare our runway under different spending scenarios\", \"how many more months do we get if we cut this\", /runway-scenario-comparison.\nmetadata:\n  category: board-decks-financial-models\n  type: base\n  cadence: monthly\n  risk: high\n  connectors: \n  integrations: \nallowed-tools: search_tool, use_tool\n---\n# /runway-scenario-comparison\n\nCompares runway across multiple concrete spend/growth scenarios (current plan, a cut plan, an accelerated-spend plan) and names the specific operational trade-off behind each scenario's extra or reduced months - not just a runway number in isolation.\n\n## Works with\n\nUse this as a portable `SKILL.md` in Grok, Claude, Cursor, Codex, VS Code agent skills, or any AI workspace that supports reusable markdown instructions. If a tool does not support slash commands, paste the task and ask the AI to follow this skill.\n\n## When to use\n\nThe team is deciding whether to cut spend, hold the current plan, or accelerate investment (hiring, marketing spend) and needs to see runway under each option side by side with the real operational consequence of each - not just \"we have X months left,\" which doesn't help decide what to actually do about it.\n\n## Inputs to gather\n\nCheck context first; ask at most one question if a missing detail changes the comparison (e.g. \"is revenue growth held flat across scenarios, or does the cut scenario also assume slower growth as a consequence?\").\n- Current cash balance and monthly burn rate\n- The specific spend changes under consideration (which roles/programs would be cut, which would be added, by how much and starting when)\n- Current revenue growth trajectory and whether any scenario assumes it changes as a consequence of the spend change (a marketing cut plausibly slows growth, not just burn)\n- Any hard external constraint (a funding round targeted for a specific future date, a board-mandated runway floor)\n\n## Safety\n\n- Propose before acting: present the comparison for review before it's used to justify any actual hiring freeze, layoff, or spend cut decision.\n- Never take an irreversible action (announcing a cut, executing a layoff) based solely on this comparison without explicit user confirmation and, where relevant, appropriate HR/legal review.\n\n## Workflow\n\n1. Build each scenario from the same current cash and burn baseline, changing only the specific levers under consideration, so the scenarios are genuinely comparable rather than each built on slightly different unstated assumptions.\n2. For a cut scenario, don't hold revenue growth constant by default - state explicitly whether the cut is assumed to affect growth (cutting sales headcount plausibly slows new revenue, cutting a back-office role plausibly doesn't) since treating every cut as growth-neutral overstates the runway benefit of cuts that actually touch revenue-generating functions.\n3. For an accelerated-spend scenario, state the specific bet being funded (a sales team expansion expected to accelerate growth by a stated amount, a product bet with a longer payoff horizon) and be explicit about the assumption's uncertainty, not just its optimistic case.\n4. Express each scenario's outcome as both a runway-in-months figure and the plain-language operational description of what that scenario actually looks like day-to-day (team size, what stops happening, what gets prioritized) since two scenarios can show similar runway numbers while representing very different operational realities.\n5. Check each scenario against any hard external constraint (a funding round targeted for month 14, a board-mandated minimum runway floor) and flag directly whether that scenario clears or misses the constraint - a scenario comparison that doesn't reference the actual constraint driving the decision is missing its most important context.\n6. Present the trade-off explicitly as \"X extra months of runway costs you Y specific operational capability\" rather than presenting cuts as a free lunch - every additional month of runway from cutting spend has a named cost, and naming it is the actual point of the comparison.\n\n## Output format\n\n**Runway Scenario Comparison - [Date] - Current Cash: [$X], Current Monthly Burn: [$Y]**\n- Scenarios table: `Scenario | Monthly Burn | Runway (Months) | Growth Assumption | Hits External Constraint? (Y/N)`\n- What Each Scenario Actually Looks Like (operational description per scenario - team size, what stops, what continues)\n- The Trade-Off Stated Plainly (e.g. \"the cut scenario buys 4 extra months but assumes a 15% slower growth rate due to the sales headcount reduction\")\n- Constraint Check (does each scenario clear the target funding date / board-mandated floor)\n- Recommended Scenario (if asked to recommend, stated with the specific reasoning, held for the user's decision - not unilaterally enacted)\n\n## Do\n- Build all scenarios from an identical baseline, varying only the specific levers under consideration.\n- State explicitly whether a cut scenario assumes any growth impact, rather than defaulting every cut to growth-neutral.\n- Name the specific operational cost behind every extra month of runway gained - no scenario comparison should imply a free lunch.\n\n## Don't\n- Don't present a spend cut as pure runway extension without naming what capability or growth rate it costs.\n- Don't recommend or imply a layoff/hiring freeze decision has been made - this is planning support, and any real action needs explicit human sign-off (and HR/legal review where relevant).\n- Don't omit the check against a hard external constraint (funding timeline, board floor) if one exists - it's usually the actual reason the comparison is being run.\n\n## Quality check (before responding)\n- [ ] Output is copy-paste-ready\n- [ ] Works outside Grok - no unexplained tool-specific assumption left in the text\n- [ ] Connector access verified before claiming results (if applicable)\n- [ ] Approval gate present for any risky/irreversible action (if applicable)\n- [ ] Every scenario's runway gain or loss is paired with a named operational trade-off, not presented as a number alone\n```\n\nAfter writing the file, confirm it exists. The user can then run /runway-scenario-comparison or describe the task from the skill description.", "skillContent": "---\nname: runway-scenario-comparison\ndescription: >\n  Compares runway under multiple spend/growth scenarios and names the specific operational trade-off behind each extra month of runway, instead of a single runway number with no visibility into what buys more time. Triggers: \"compare our runway under different spending scenarios\", \"how many more months do we get if we cut this\", /runway-scenario-comparison.\nmetadata:\n  category: board-decks-financial-models\n  type: base\n  cadence: monthly\n  risk: high\n  connectors: \n  integrations: \nallowed-tools: search_tool, use_tool\n---\n# /runway-scenario-comparison\n\nCompares runway across multiple concrete spend/growth scenarios (current plan, a cut plan, an accelerated-spend plan) and names the specific operational trade-off behind each scenario's extra or reduced months - not just a runway number in isolation.\n\n## Works with\n\nUse this as a portable `SKILL.md` in Grok, Claude, Cursor, Codex, VS Code agent skills, or any AI workspace that supports reusable markdown instructions. If a tool does not support slash commands, paste the task and ask the AI to follow this skill.\n\n## When to use\n\nThe team is deciding whether to cut spend, hold the current plan, or accelerate investment (hiring, marketing spend) and needs to see runway under each option side by side with the real operational consequence of each - not just \"we have X months left,\" which doesn't help decide what to actually do about it.\n\n## Inputs to gather\n\nCheck context first; ask at most one question if a missing detail changes the comparison (e.g. \"is revenue growth held flat across scenarios, or does the cut scenario also assume slower growth as a consequence?\").\n- Current cash balance and monthly burn rate\n- The specific spend changes under consideration (which roles/programs would be cut, which would be added, by how much and starting when)\n- Current revenue growth trajectory and whether any scenario assumes it changes as a consequence of the spend change (a marketing cut plausibly slows growth, not just burn)\n- Any hard external constraint (a funding round targeted for a specific future date, a board-mandated runway floor)\n\n## Safety\n\n- Propose before acting: present the comparison for review before it's used to justify any actual hiring freeze, layoff, or spend cut decision.\n- Never take an irreversible action (announcing a cut, executing a layoff) based solely on this comparison without explicit user confirmation and, where relevant, appropriate HR/legal review.\n\n## Workflow\n\n1. Build each scenario from the same current cash and burn baseline, changing only the specific levers under consideration, so the scenarios are genuinely comparable rather than each built on slightly different unstated assumptions.\n2. For a cut scenario, don't hold revenue growth constant by default - state explicitly whether the cut is assumed to affect growth (cutting sales headcount plausibly slows new revenue, cutting a back-office role plausibly doesn't) since treating every cut as growth-neutral overstates the runway benefit of cuts that actually touch revenue-generating functions.\n3. For an accelerated-spend scenario, state the specific bet being funded (a sales team expansion expected to accelerate growth by a stated amount, a product bet with a longer payoff horizon) and be explicit about the assumption's uncertainty, not just its optimistic case.\n4. Express each scenario's outcome as both a runway-in-months figure and the plain-language operational description of what that scenario actually looks like day-to-day (team size, what stops happening, what gets prioritized) since two scenarios can show similar runway numbers while representing very different operational realities.\n5. Check each scenario against any hard external constraint (a funding round targeted for month 14, a board-mandated minimum runway floor) and flag directly whether that scenario clears or misses the constraint - a scenario comparison that doesn't reference the actual constraint driving the decision is missing its most important context.\n6. Present the trade-off explicitly as \"X extra months of runway costs you Y specific operational capability\" rather than presenting cuts as a free lunch - every additional month of runway from cutting spend has a named cost, and naming it is the actual point of the comparison.\n\n## Output format\n\n**Runway Scenario Comparison - [Date] - Current Cash: [$X], Current Monthly Burn: [$Y]**\n- Scenarios table: `Scenario | Monthly Burn | Runway (Months) | Growth Assumption | Hits External Constraint? (Y/N)`\n- What Each Scenario Actually Looks Like (operational description per scenario - team size, what stops, what continues)\n- The Trade-Off Stated Plainly (e.g. \"the cut scenario buys 4 extra months but assumes a 15% slower growth rate due to the sales headcount reduction\")\n- Constraint Check (does each scenario clear the target funding date / board-mandated floor)\n- Recommended Scenario (if asked to recommend, stated with the specific reasoning, held for the user's decision - not unilaterally enacted)\n\n## Do\n- Build all scenarios from an identical baseline, varying only the specific levers under consideration.\n- State explicitly whether a cut scenario assumes any growth impact, rather than defaulting every cut to growth-neutral.\n- Name the specific operational cost behind every extra month of runway gained - no scenario comparison should imply a free lunch.\n\n## Don't\n- Don't present a spend cut as pure runway extension without naming what capability or growth rate it costs.\n- Don't recommend or imply a layoff/hiring freeze decision has been made - this is planning support, and any real action needs explicit human sign-off (and HR/legal review where relevant).\n- Don't omit the check against a hard external constraint (funding timeline, board floor) if one exists - it's usually the actual reason the comparison is being run.\n\n## Quality check (before responding)\n- [ ] Output is copy-paste-ready\n- [ ] Works outside Grok - no unexplained tool-specific assumption left in the text\n- [ ] Connector access verified before claiming results (if applicable)\n- [ ] Approval gate present for any risky/irreversible action (if applicable)\n- [ ] Every scenario's runway gain or loss is paired with a named operational trade-off, not presented as a number alone\n"}, {"id": "scenario-model-narrative", "aiInstallPrompt": "Install the skill 'scenario-model-narrative' by writing the file below.\n\nUniversal path: ./skills/scenario-model-narrative/SKILL.md\nGrok path: ~/.grok/skills/scenario-model-narrative/SKILL.md\nCursor path: ~/.cursor/skills/scenario-model-narrative/SKILL.md\nClaude path: ~/.claude/skills/scenario-model-narrative/SKILL.md\nVS Code agent path: .github/skills/scenario-model-narrative/SKILL.md\n\nCreate the folder if needed, then write SKILL.md with this exact content:\n\n```markdown\n---\nname: scenario-model-narrative\ndescription: >\n  Turns a set of financial scenario numbers (base/upside/downside) into a narrative that explains the specific assumption driving each scenario apart, instead of three tables that all look plausible with no explanation of why they'd diverge. Triggers: \"write the narrative for our scenario model\", \"explain these three financial scenarios to the board\", /scenario-model-narrative.\nmetadata:\n  category: board-decks-financial-models\n  type: base\n  cadence: on-demand\n  risk: medium\n  connectors: \n  integrations: \nallowed-tools: search_tool, use_tool\n---\n# /scenario-model-narrative\n\nTurns a base/upside/downside financial scenario model into a narrative that explains the specific, falsifiable assumption driving each scenario apart from the others, so a reader understands why the numbers diverge and what would tell you which scenario is actually playing out.\n\n## Works with\n\nUse this as a portable `SKILL.md` in Grok, Claude, Cursor, Codex, VS Code agent skills, or any AI workspace that supports reusable markdown instructions. If a tool does not support slash commands, paste the task and ask the AI to follow this skill.\n\n## When to use\n\nYou've built (or been handed) a multi-scenario financial model - base case, upside, downside, or several strategic paths - and need a written narrative to accompany it for a board deck, investor update, or internal planning doc, because the raw numbers alone don't explain why the scenarios differ or which early signals would tell you which one is unfolding.\n\n## Inputs to gather\n\nCheck context first; ask at most one question if a missing detail changes the narrative (e.g. \"is the downside case triggered by a specific external event, or just a slower version of the base case?\").\n- The scenario numbers themselves (revenue, burn, headcount, or whatever the model covers, across each scenario)\n- The specific assumption(s) that differ between scenarios (conversion rate, sales cycle length, churn rate, a specific deal closing or not, a funding round timing)\n- The audience (board, investors, internal leadership) since the level of detail and the framing of risk differ\n- Any leading indicators already being tracked that would signal which scenario is materializing\n- The time horizon the model covers\n\n## Workflow\n\n1. Identify the one or two assumptions that actually drive the divergence between scenarios - not a restated list of every input, but specifically which lever, when changed, is why the downside case looks different from the base case (e.g., \"the downside case is driven entirely by a 3-month slip in enterprise deal closing, not a change in win rate\").\n2. State each scenario's core assumption as a specific, falsifiable claim (\"we close the two enterprise deals currently in late-stage by end of Q3\") rather than a vague qualitative label (\"if things go well\") - a falsifiable assumption is one you can actually check against reality later.\n3. Explain the downside case honestly as a real, plausible path, not a strawman built to make the base case look conservative by comparison - a downside case that's clearly implausible undermines the credibility of the whole model.\n4. Name the specific leading indicators that would tell the reader, before the period ends, which scenario is playing out - this is what makes a scenario model actionable rather than purely retrospective (\"we'll know we're tracking downside if the two enterprise deals haven't reached signature stage by mid-Q3\").\n5. State the actual decision or action tied to each scenario materializing - what changes operationally if downside starts to look real (a hiring pause, a spend cut) versus what happens if upside is tracking (an accelerated hire plan) - since a scenario model without attached decisions is just an FYI, not a planning tool.\n6. Keep the narrative anchored to the model's actual numbers throughout - reference specific figures from each scenario rather than describing them only in qualitative terms, so the narrative and the underlying model stay tightly linked.\n\n## Output format\n\n**Scenario Model Narrative - [Model Name/Period]**\n- Scenarios at a Glance table: `Scenario | Key Metric(s) | vs. Base Case`\n- The Core Divergent Assumption(s) (1-2 sentences per scenario, stated as falsifiable claims)\n- Why the Downside Case Is a Real Risk, Not a Strawman\n- Leading Indicators to Watch (specific, checkable signals per scenario, with rough timing)\n- Decisions Tied to Each Scenario (what changes operationally if this scenario starts to materialize)\n\n## Do\n- Name the specific one or two assumptions actually driving scenario divergence, not a restated list of every model input.\n- State each assumption as a falsifiable, checkable claim, not a vague qualitative label.\n- Tie a concrete operational decision to each scenario so the model functions as a planning tool, not just a projection exercise.\n\n## Don't\n- Don't write a downside case as an obvious strawman meant to flatter the base case by comparison - make it a genuinely plausible path.\n- Don't describe scenarios only qualitatively without anchoring back to the actual model numbers.\n- Don't leave the leading-indicators section generic (\"watch the market\") - name the specific, trackable signal for this business.\n\n## Quality check (before responding)\n- [ ] Output is copy-paste-ready\n- [ ] Works outside Grok - no unexplained tool-specific assumption left in the text\n- [ ] Connector access verified before claiming results (if applicable)\n- [ ] Approval gate present for any risky/irreversible action (if applicable)\n- [ ] Each scenario's core assumption is written as a specific, falsifiable claim, not a vague qualitative label\n```\n\nAfter writing the file, confirm it exists. The user can then run /scenario-model-narrative or describe the task from the skill description.", "skillContent": "---\nname: scenario-model-narrative\ndescription: >\n  Turns a set of financial scenario numbers (base/upside/downside) into a narrative that explains the specific assumption driving each scenario apart, instead of three tables that all look plausible with no explanation of why they'd diverge. Triggers: \"write the narrative for our scenario model\", \"explain these three financial scenarios to the board\", /scenario-model-narrative.\nmetadata:\n  category: board-decks-financial-models\n  type: base\n  cadence: on-demand\n  risk: medium\n  connectors: \n  integrations: \nallowed-tools: search_tool, use_tool\n---\n# /scenario-model-narrative\n\nTurns a base/upside/downside financial scenario model into a narrative that explains the specific, falsifiable assumption driving each scenario apart from the others, so a reader understands why the numbers diverge and what would tell you which scenario is actually playing out.\n\n## Works with\n\nUse this as a portable `SKILL.md` in Grok, Claude, Cursor, Codex, VS Code agent skills, or any AI workspace that supports reusable markdown instructions. If a tool does not support slash commands, paste the task and ask the AI to follow this skill.\n\n## When to use\n\nYou've built (or been handed) a multi-scenario financial model - base case, upside, downside, or several strategic paths - and need a written narrative to accompany it for a board deck, investor update, or internal planning doc, because the raw numbers alone don't explain why the scenarios differ or which early signals would tell you which one is unfolding.\n\n## Inputs to gather\n\nCheck context first; ask at most one question if a missing detail changes the narrative (e.g. \"is the downside case triggered by a specific external event, or just a slower version of the base case?\").\n- The scenario numbers themselves (revenue, burn, headcount, or whatever the model covers, across each scenario)\n- The specific assumption(s) that differ between scenarios (conversion rate, sales cycle length, churn rate, a specific deal closing or not, a funding round timing)\n- The audience (board, investors, internal leadership) since the level of detail and the framing of risk differ\n- Any leading indicators already being tracked that would signal which scenario is materializing\n- The time horizon the model covers\n\n## Workflow\n\n1. Identify the one or two assumptions that actually drive the divergence between scenarios - not a restated list of every input, but specifically which lever, when changed, is why the downside case looks different from the base case (e.g., \"the downside case is driven entirely by a 3-month slip in enterprise deal closing, not a change in win rate\").\n2. State each scenario's core assumption as a specific, falsifiable claim (\"we close the two enterprise deals currently in late-stage by end of Q3\") rather than a vague qualitative label (\"if things go well\") - a falsifiable assumption is one you can actually check against reality later.\n3. Explain the downside case honestly as a real, plausible path, not a strawman built to make the base case look conservative by comparison - a downside case that's clearly implausible undermines the credibility of the whole model.\n4. Name the specific leading indicators that would tell the reader, before the period ends, which scenario is playing out - this is what makes a scenario model actionable rather than purely retrospective (\"we'll know we're tracking downside if the two enterprise deals haven't reached signature stage by mid-Q3\").\n5. State the actual decision or action tied to each scenario materializing - what changes operationally if downside starts to look real (a hiring pause, a spend cut) versus what happens if upside is tracking (an accelerated hire plan) - since a scenario model without attached decisions is just an FYI, not a planning tool.\n6. Keep the narrative anchored to the model's actual numbers throughout - reference specific figures from each scenario rather than describing them only in qualitative terms, so the narrative and the underlying model stay tightly linked.\n\n## Output format\n\n**Scenario Model Narrative - [Model Name/Period]**\n- Scenarios at a Glance table: `Scenario | Key Metric(s) | vs. Base Case`\n- The Core Divergent Assumption(s) (1-2 sentences per scenario, stated as falsifiable claims)\n- Why the Downside Case Is a Real Risk, Not a Strawman\n- Leading Indicators to Watch (specific, checkable signals per scenario, with rough timing)\n- Decisions Tied to Each Scenario (what changes operationally if this scenario starts to materialize)\n\n## Do\n- Name the specific one or two assumptions actually driving scenario divergence, not a restated list of every model input.\n- State each assumption as a falsifiable, checkable claim, not a vague qualitative label.\n- Tie a concrete operational decision to each scenario so the model functions as a planning tool, not just a projection exercise.\n\n## Don't\n- Don't write a downside case as an obvious strawman meant to flatter the base case by comparison - make it a genuinely plausible path.\n- Don't describe scenarios only qualitatively without anchoring back to the actual model numbers.\n- Don't leave the leading-indicators section generic (\"watch the market\") - name the specific, trackable signal for this business.\n\n## Quality check (before responding)\n- [ ] Output is copy-paste-ready\n- [ ] Works outside Grok - no unexplained tool-specific assumption left in the text\n- [ ] Connector access verified before claiming results (if applicable)\n- [ ] Approval gate present for any risky/irreversible action (if applicable)\n- [ ] Each scenario's core assumption is written as a specific, falsifiable claim, not a vague qualitative label\n"}, {"id": "unit-economics-explainer", "aiInstallPrompt": "Install the skill 'unit-economics-explainer' by writing the file below.\n\nUniversal path: ./skills/unit-economics-explainer/SKILL.md\nGrok path: ~/.grok/skills/unit-economics-explainer/SKILL.md\nCursor path: ~/.cursor/skills/unit-economics-explainer/SKILL.md\nClaude path: ~/.claude/skills/unit-economics-explainer/SKILL.md\nVS Code agent path: .github/skills/unit-economics-explainer/SKILL.md\n\nCreate the folder if needed, then write SKILL.md with this exact content:\n\n```markdown\n---\nname: unit-economics-explainer\ndescription: >\n  Turns raw CAC/LTV/margin inputs into a plain-language unit economics explainer that shows the calculation's assumptions and states plainly whether the business model actually works at the unit level. Triggers: \"explain our unit economics to the board\", \"walk through whether our CAC and LTV actually make sense\", /unit-economics-explainer.\nmetadata:\n  category: board-decks-financial-models\n  type: base\n  cadence: on-demand\n  risk: medium\n  connectors: \n  integrations: \nallowed-tools: search_tool, use_tool\n---\n# /unit-economics-explainer\n\nTurns raw CAC, LTV, margin, and payback inputs into a plain-language explainer that shows its work on every assumption and states directly whether the unit economics actually support the business model at this stage, not just recites the ratios.\n\n## Works with\n\nUse this as a portable `SKILL.md` in Grok, Claude, Cursor, Codex, VS Code agent skills, or any AI workspace that supports reusable markdown instructions. If a tool does not support slash commands, paste the task and ask the AI to follow this skill.\n\n## When to use\n\nBefore a fundraising conversation, a board discussion on whether to scale spend on a given channel, or an internal debate about whether the business model actually works - when you need someone to walk through what's actually behind the CAC/LTV numbers rather than just quoting a ratio that sounds fine in isolation.\n\n## Inputs to gather\n\nCheck context first; ask at most one question if a missing detail changes the read (e.g. \"is this CAC blended across all channels, or specific to one you're deciding whether to scale?\").\n- The raw inputs: acquisition cost by channel if available, average revenue per customer, gross margin, churn/retention rate, average customer lifetime or contract length\n- Whether CAC is fully loaded (includes sales team salaries, tooling, overhead) or ad-spend only, since this materially changes the real number\n- The stage/context this is being used for (fundraising narrative, internal scale-spend decision, board update)\n- Any known cohort variation (new customers behaving differently from customers acquired a year ago) if that data exists\n\n## Workflow\n\n1. State exactly what's included in the CAC figure being used (fully-loaded including sales/marketing headcount and tools, or narrow ad-spend-only) since these can differ by 2-3x for the same business, and using the narrow version to make the ratio look better is a common, easily-spotted red flag for anyone doing real diligence.\n2. Show the LTV calculation's actual assumption chain (average revenue per period × gross margin × expected customer lifetime, with expected lifetime typically derived from churn rate) rather than presenting LTV as a single number with no visible derivation - an LTV without shown assumptions can't be sanity-checked by the reader.\n3. Flag the single most fragile assumption in the LTV calculation explicitly - usually the retention/churn rate, since small changes in churn compound dramatically into large changes in lifetime value, more than most other inputs in the model.\n4. Calculate and state the payback period (time to recover CAC from gross margin dollars) alongside the LTV:CAC ratio, since a business can have a healthy-looking ratio but an unsustainably long payback period that creates real cash flow strain regardless of the ratio's health.\n5. If channel-level data exists, break out unit economics by channel rather than presenting one blended figure, since blended CAC/LTV often masks one channel that's excellent and another that's actively losing money, and a scale-spend decision needs the channel-level view, not the blend.\n6. State a direct verdict on whether the unit economics currently support the business model at this stage of growth (works today, works only if churn improves, doesn't yet work and here's the gap) rather than leaving the reader to infer a conclusion from the ratios alone.\n7. Note explicitly if the data underlying this analysis is thin (new business, small cohort size, short observed history) since early unit economics with limited data carry real uncertainty that shouldn't be presented with false precision.\n\n## Output format\n\n**Unit Economics Explainer - [Business/Channel] - [Date]**\n- Inputs Used (CAC definition - fully-loaded or ad-spend-only - plus ARPU, gross margin, churn/retention)\n- LTV Calculation Shown (assumption chain, not just the output number)\n- Most Fragile Assumption (usually churn) and Why It Matters Disproportionately\n- LTV:CAC Ratio and Payback Period (both stated, not just the ratio)\n- By-Channel Breakdown (if data allows - don't rely on a blended figure alone)\n- Verdict: Works Today / Works If [Specific Condition] Improves / Doesn't Yet Work - stated directly\n- Data Confidence Note (flag if based on thin/early data)\n\n## Do\n- State explicitly whether CAC is fully-loaded or narrow - this single choice changes the whole analysis's credibility.\n- Show the LTV assumption chain, not just the output figure.\n- Give a direct verdict on whether the model works at the unit level right now, not just a ratio for the reader to interpret.\n\n## Don't\n- Don't use a narrow ad-spend-only CAC to make the ratio look better without disclosing that choice - it's a common and easily-detected red flag.\n- Don't present LTV:CAC ratio without also stating payback period; a healthy ratio can still hide a cash-strain-inducing payback timeline.\n- Don't present unit economics from a small or early cohort with the same confidence as a mature, well-observed business - flag the data thinness.\n\n## Quality check (before responding)\n- [ ] Output is copy-paste-ready\n- [ ] Works outside Grok - no unexplained tool-specific assumption left in the text\n- [ ] Connector access verified before claiming results (if applicable)\n- [ ] Approval gate present for any risky/irreversible action (if applicable)\n- [ ] The CAC definition (fully-loaded vs. ad-spend-only) is stated explicitly, and a direct works/doesn't-work verdict is given, not left implicit\n```\n\nAfter writing the file, confirm it exists. The user can then run /unit-economics-explainer or describe the task from the skill description.", "skillContent": "---\nname: unit-economics-explainer\ndescription: >\n  Turns raw CAC/LTV/margin inputs into a plain-language unit economics explainer that shows the calculation's assumptions and states plainly whether the business model actually works at the unit level. Triggers: \"explain our unit economics to the board\", \"walk through whether our CAC and LTV actually make sense\", /unit-economics-explainer.\nmetadata:\n  category: board-decks-financial-models\n  type: base\n  cadence: on-demand\n  risk: medium\n  connectors: \n  integrations: \nallowed-tools: search_tool, use_tool\n---\n# /unit-economics-explainer\n\nTurns raw CAC, LTV, margin, and payback inputs into a plain-language explainer that shows its work on every assumption and states directly whether the unit economics actually support the business model at this stage, not just recites the ratios.\n\n## Works with\n\nUse this as a portable `SKILL.md` in Grok, Claude, Cursor, Codex, VS Code agent skills, or any AI workspace that supports reusable markdown instructions. If a tool does not support slash commands, paste the task and ask the AI to follow this skill.\n\n## When to use\n\nBefore a fundraising conversation, a board discussion on whether to scale spend on a given channel, or an internal debate about whether the business model actually works - when you need someone to walk through what's actually behind the CAC/LTV numbers rather than just quoting a ratio that sounds fine in isolation.\n\n## Inputs to gather\n\nCheck context first; ask at most one question if a missing detail changes the read (e.g. \"is this CAC blended across all channels, or specific to one you're deciding whether to scale?\").\n- The raw inputs: acquisition cost by channel if available, average revenue per customer, gross margin, churn/retention rate, average customer lifetime or contract length\n- Whether CAC is fully loaded (includes sales team salaries, tooling, overhead) or ad-spend only, since this materially changes the real number\n- The stage/context this is being used for (fundraising narrative, internal scale-spend decision, board update)\n- Any known cohort variation (new customers behaving differently from customers acquired a year ago) if that data exists\n\n## Workflow\n\n1. State exactly what's included in the CAC figure being used (fully-loaded including sales/marketing headcount and tools, or narrow ad-spend-only) since these can differ by 2-3x for the same business, and using the narrow version to make the ratio look better is a common, easily-spotted red flag for anyone doing real diligence.\n2. Show the LTV calculation's actual assumption chain (average revenue per period × gross margin × expected customer lifetime, with expected lifetime typically derived from churn rate) rather than presenting LTV as a single number with no visible derivation - an LTV without shown assumptions can't be sanity-checked by the reader.\n3. Flag the single most fragile assumption in the LTV calculation explicitly - usually the retention/churn rate, since small changes in churn compound dramatically into large changes in lifetime value, more than most other inputs in the model.\n4. Calculate and state the payback period (time to recover CAC from gross margin dollars) alongside the LTV:CAC ratio, since a business can have a healthy-looking ratio but an unsustainably long payback period that creates real cash flow strain regardless of the ratio's health.\n5. If channel-level data exists, break out unit economics by channel rather than presenting one blended figure, since blended CAC/LTV often masks one channel that's excellent and another that's actively losing money, and a scale-spend decision needs the channel-level view, not the blend.\n6. State a direct verdict on whether the unit economics currently support the business model at this stage of growth (works today, works only if churn improves, doesn't yet work and here's the gap) rather than leaving the reader to infer a conclusion from the ratios alone.\n7. Note explicitly if the data underlying this analysis is thin (new business, small cohort size, short observed history) since early unit economics with limited data carry real uncertainty that shouldn't be presented with false precision.\n\n## Output format\n\n**Unit Economics Explainer - [Business/Channel] - [Date]**\n- Inputs Used (CAC definition - fully-loaded or ad-spend-only - plus ARPU, gross margin, churn/retention)\n- LTV Calculation Shown (assumption chain, not just the output number)\n- Most Fragile Assumption (usually churn) and Why It Matters Disproportionately\n- LTV:CAC Ratio and Payback Period (both stated, not just the ratio)\n- By-Channel Breakdown (if data allows - don't rely on a blended figure alone)\n- Verdict: Works Today / Works If [Specific Condition] Improves / Doesn't Yet Work - stated directly\n- Data Confidence Note (flag if based on thin/early data)\n\n## Do\n- State explicitly whether CAC is fully-loaded or narrow - this single choice changes the whole analysis's credibility.\n- Show the LTV assumption chain, not just the output figure.\n- Give a direct verdict on whether the model works at the unit level right now, not just a ratio for the reader to interpret.\n\n## Don't\n- Don't use a narrow ad-spend-only CAC to make the ratio look better without disclosing that choice - it's a common and easily-detected red flag.\n- Don't present LTV:CAC ratio without also stating payback period; a healthy ratio can still hide a cash-strain-inducing payback timeline.\n- Don't present unit economics from a small or early cohort with the same confidence as a mature, well-observed business - flag the data thinness.\n\n## Quality check (before responding)\n- [ ] Output is copy-paste-ready\n- [ ] Works outside Grok - no unexplained tool-specific assumption left in the text\n- [ ] Connector access verified before claiming results (if applicable)\n- [ ] Approval gate present for any risky/irreversible action (if applicable)\n- [ ] The CAC definition (fully-loaded vs. ad-spend-only) is stated explicitly, and a direct works/doesn't-work verdict is given, not left implicit\n"}]};
